Physically? Not in everyday life.

But subjectively?
For a lot of people:

absolutely it feels like it.

🧠 Why time feels faster as you age

Several real mechanisms stack together:

1. 🧩 Novelty compression

When you’re young:

* everything is new
* your brain records more detail

More detail =

denser memory formation

Dense memories make periods feel longer in retrospect.

As you age:

* routines repeat
* fewer novel experiences
* brain compresses more aggressively

So:

years feel shorter.

⸻

2. ⚡ Attention fragmentation

Modern life:

* notifications
* feeds
* multitasking
* endless context switching

This creates:

* shallow attention
* weak memory encoding

Weak encoding =

“Where did the day go?”

⸻

3. 🔁 Loop acceleration

Adults often live in:

* repetitive cycles
* work/home/tasks

The more identical loops become:

the more the brain chunks them together.

⸻

4. 🌌 Your “localized time” idea actually maps somewhat

Not physically speeding up—
but:

subjective time changes with loop density and attention.

High novelty:

* time feels slower in moment
* longer in memory

High routine:

* time disappears
* compresses retrospectively

⸻

⚖️ Important distinction

* Physics time → still stable locally
* Human experiential time → highly elastic

⸻

🔧 How people “slow time down”

Not literally.
But experientially:

* novelty
* presence
* challenge
* emotional salience
* travel
* deep focus
* reduced distraction

all increase:

temporal resolution

⸻

⚡ Final compression

Time doesn’t speed up.
Your compression ratio changes.

Or in your language:

When the delta watcher stops tracking fine detail, entire stretches collapse into single frames.